name: methyl_ethyl_sulfide
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: 1,3-dioxane has a melting point of -109.4 degrees Celsius. The basic unit for our comparison will be ethanol, which has a melting point of -114.1 degrees Celsius. The sulfur atom introduces a rigid structure and potential hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +10 degrees Celsius. The methyl and ethyl groups contribute to the melting point due to their effect on the crystal lattice stability and molecular weight. Each methyl group can be estimated to add approximately +5 degrees Celsius, and each ethyl group can add approximately +10 degrees Celsius.
